  {
    "index": 3,
    "hash": "uGRPFVJhNk84AeG8VsTvxmPv2zA=",
    "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:33.000Z",
    "action": {
      "type": "SET_CONTENT",
      "input": {
        "content": "## Decision: drive-level first, document-level later\n\n### Phase 1 \u2014 drive-level collaboration (first ship)\n\n- Simpler mental model: \"I'm collaborating on this whole drive with Alice and Bob.\"\n- Covers the drive ops (`ADD_FOLDER`, `MOVE_NODE`, `ADD_FILE`) and every doc inside the drive.\n- A **single ACT grant per participant** covers the drive manifest, all child doc manifests, and all op batches \u2014 minimizing ACT chain management.\n\n### Phase 2 \u2014 document-level collaboration\n\n- Narrower: \"I'm collaborating on this one doc, but keep the rest of the drive private.\"\n- ACT grantee list is scoped to one doc's manifest and op batches only.\n- The drive manifest itself is **not** shared \u2014 participants see a free-standing doc, not its parent drive.\n- Useful when the containing drive has confidential material and only one doc is meant for outside eyes.\n\nDrive-level first is the right build order because the mental model is simpler for users, a single ACT scope is easier to reason about, and it still exercises every layer of the mesh (manifest, peer feeds, GSOC, signatures). Document-level scoping then narrows the ACT chain without changing the plumbing.",
        "updatedAt": "2026-05-13T13:00:33.000Z"
      },
      "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:33.000Z"
    }
  },
